# This would normally contain a base64-encoded AWS Nitro attestation document
# For testing purposes, you should replace this with a real attestation document
# obtained from your AWS Nitro Enclave environment

# Example structure (this is not a real attestation):
# - ModuleID: AWS Nitro Enclave module identifier
# - PCRs: Platform Configuration Registers with measured boot values
# - Certificate: X.509 certificate for signature verification
# - CABundle: Certificate chain to AWS Nitro root
# - Optional: UserData, PublicKey, Nonce for application-specific data

# To generate a real attestation document:
# 1. Create and run a Nitro Enclave
# 2. From within the enclave, call the attestation API
# 3. The document will be signed by AWS and contain your specific PCR values

# Example PCR values you might see in AWS Nitro attestations:
# PCR[0]: Platform firmware measurement
# PCR[1]: Linux kernel measurement  
# PCR[2]: User application measurement
# PCR[3]: Additional application measurement (if applicable)
# PCR[4]: Boot loader measurement
# PCR[8]: Certificate of the Attestation Public Key

# For actual testing, replace this file with a real base64-encoded attestation
